          "body": "Verse 7 is the chapter's rhetorical and theological center: 'For they sow the wind and they reap the whirlwind.' This is not decoration; it is the chapter's governing epistemology about sin and consequence. Agricultural proverbs in the wisdom tradition describe the moral structure of the created order — Proverbs 22:8 ('He who sows iniquity will reap vanity') and Galatians 6:7–8 ('whatever a man sows, this he will also reap') belong to the same canonical insight. The wind (*ruach*) is empty, futile — you cannot harvest wind. But the whirlwind (*suphah*) is the word for a storm, a tempest, a destructive gale. The proportion between cause and consequence is staggering: small, empty seed produces overwhelming, catastrophic harvest. Israel's idolatry and political maneuvering seem manageable in the moment; the whirlwind of Assyrian conquest will not be. The proverb then extends the image into agricultural failure (8:7b): the standing grain has no heads, yields no flour — and even if it did, strangers (Assyrians) would consume it. The covenant curses of Leviticus 26:16 and Deuteronomy 28:33 are in view: 'you will sow your seed uselessly, for your enemies will eat it up.'"
