        "title": "Multiplied altars, disregarded law — religion without the covenant",
        "range": "8:11-13",
        "excerpt": "Since Ephraim has multiplied altars for sin, they have become altars of sinning for him. Though I wrote for him ten thousand precepts of My law, they are regarded as a strange thing.",
        "body": "Verse 11 is one of the most theologically precise statements in the chapter, and it turns on a single Hebrew wordplay. Ephraim has multiplied altars *for sin* — that is, for sin-offerings, the prescribed sacrificial mechanism for dealing with covenant transgression (Leviticus 4–5). But instead of functioning as instruments of atonement, these altars have become altars *of sinning* — the instrument of expiation has been converted into an instrument of accumulation of guilt. The word *chata* appears in both halves of the verse, first as 'sin-offering' and then as 'to sin.' The multiplication of cultic infrastructure without the reality of covenant repentance does not neutralize guilt; it compounds it. More altars, more sin.\n\nThis is the prophetic critique of ritual without relationship that runs from Amos 5:21–24 through Isaiah 1:11–15 through Jesus's confrontations with the Pharisees. The problem is not that Israel has no religious activity — it has abundant religious activity, multiplied altars, elaborate sacrificial systems. The problem is that none of it is grounded in the covenant reality of *yada* — the intimate, obedient, relational knowledge of Yahweh. The altars have become the place where Israel performs religion while avoiding the God religion is supposed to bring near.\n\nVerse 12 is a devastation: 'Though I wrote for him ten thousand precepts of My law, they are regarded as a strange thing.' The emphasis on *writing* (*katav*) is significant — this is not merely oral tradition that might have been forgotten in transmission but the inscribed, fixed, durable revelation of God. Yahweh wrote; the obligation to attend to the written word is categorical. The number *ribbo* (ten thousand) is the Hebrew hyperbole for abundance — Yahweh's revelation was generous, comprehensive, accessible. Israel's response was to treat it as *zur* — foreign, alien, strange, as though it belonged to someone else's culture. Peter Davids's comment on the parallel in James 1:22–24 is apposite: the hearer who walks away from the mirror forgetting what he looked like has done precisely what Israel does here with the written law.\n\nVerse 13 closes the indictment of cultic activity with a divine rejection that echoes Amos 5:22. 'As for My sacrificial gifts, they sacrifice the flesh and eat it, but the Lord has taken no delight in them.' The sacrificial system without covenant fidelity is not merely ineffective; it is offensive. God is watching the ritual and is unpleased. The judicial consequence follows immediately: 'Now He will remember their iniquity, and punish them for their sins; they will return to Egypt.' The word 'remember' (*zakhar*) in the Hebrew legal tradition is the activation of judicial attention — God 'remembering' iniquity is not His having previously forgotten; it is His moving from patience to active prosecution. The return to Egypt is the most severe possible statement of covenant reversal: the Exodus, the founding redemptive event of Israel's entire identity, is undone. They go back.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chata* appearing in both halves of v.11 as *sin-offering* and *sinning* — the wordplay in Hebrew (*lechat'o → chataot lahem*) cannot be reproduced in English but is unmistakable in the original. *Katav* (wrote) — the written character of Torah distinguishes Yahweh's revelation from oral tradition; the permanence of the inscription heightens Israel's culpability. *Zakhar* (remember) — in OT judicial contexts, divine remembrance is not nostalgia but prosecutorial activation."
